## Introduction

As we continue to build upon our foundation of modular, self-contained executables, it's time to address a crucial component that ties everything together: the package manager. In this article, we'll delve into the world of semver resolution, dependency graphs, cycle detection, and the tradeoffs that led us to our current solution.

### Semver Resolution

The core of any package manager is its ability to resolve version conflicts between dependencies. Lateralus tackles this using semantic versioning (semver). Our approach involves maintaining a graph of all packages, including their versions, which allows for efficient conflict resolution.

fn resolve_version_conflict(conflicts: map[string]map[string]int) -> int {
    // Iterate through all conflicting packages
    for pkg in conflicts.keys() {
        for version in conflicts[pkg].keys() {
            // Return the highest available version
            return max(version, conflicts[pkg][version])
        }
    }

    // If no higher version exists, default to latest
    return latest_version()
}

## Dependency Graphs

A robust package manager relies heavily on accurate dependency graphs. This ensures that every package's dependencies are up-to-date and correctly resolved. We've implemented an algorithm that periodically updates these graphs based on user input.

fn update_dependency_graph(graph: map[string]map[string]int) {
    // Fetch updated dependencies from users
    fetch_dependencies()

    // Update graph with new information
    for pkg in fetched_dependencies.keys() {
        if graph.contains(pkg) {
            update_graph(graph, pkg)
        } else {
            add_to_graph(graph, pkg)
        }
    }
}

fn add_to_graph(graph: map[string]map[string]int, pkg: string) {
    // Initialize package data with default values
    init_package_data(pkg)

    // Add package to graph with initial version
    graph[pkg] = { version: "1.0" }
}

## Cycle Detection

One of the most critical aspects of a package manager is preventing cycle detection – situations where two or more packages depend on each other, leading to infinite loops. Our implementation includes an algorithm that identifies such cycles early on, ensuring seamless resolution.
